  "prompt": "What function do sclerenchyma cells serve?",
  "response": "Sclerenchyma cells serve several important functions in plants, primarily related to support and protection. These cells are characterized by their thick, lignified cell walls, which provide rigidity and strength. The main functions of sclerenchyma cells include:\n\n1. **Structural Support**: Sclerenchyma cells contribute to the structural integrity of plants. They are found in various parts of the plant, such as stems, leaves, and seeds, where they help maintain shape and prevent collapse under mechanical stress.\n\n2. **Mechanical Strength**: The lignin in their cell walls makes sclerenchyma cells tough and resistant to compression and bending. This mechanical strength is crucial for supporting the plant against wind, gravity, and other environmental forces.\n\n3. **Protection**: Sclerenchyma cells can protect more delicate plant tissues by forming hard protective layers. For example, they form the tough outer shells of nuts and seeds, safeguarding the reproductive structures inside.\n\n4. **Transport**: In some plants, sclerenchyma cells, specifically sclereids and fibers, can also play a role in the transportation of water and nutrients, although this is not their primary function.\n\nOverall, sclerenchyma cells are essential for providing structural support and protection, contributing to the overall stability and durability of plants.",
